	<!-- message -->
	<p>The title of the post is so far removed from the content.<br />
<br />
edit: By this I mean that I don't agree with the post. AA are not the answer and are in fact just another way to separate the player base, this time based on ability to grind. One of the themes I feel I have seen regardless of the uber vs casual person arguing has been that artificial separation of the playerbase is bad. Well, in this way you would remove all separation but make it a long and arduous path for someone to improve their own abilities.<br />
<br />
You also make it for the attention of the SoE folks, why? Before an idea is presented to them shouldn't it be agreed on?<br />
<br />
This undermines the big argument going on about Shaman being broken, because instead of pushing for fixes, you are pushing for fixes over time, at the discretion of the shaman. So, if I want to be fixed and useful I have to grind 200 aa.<br />
<br />
Thanks Blazz, I really appreciate that.</p>
	
	
	
	
