	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Sudedor</b><br /><i>No.<br />
<br />
Just . . . no.<br />
<br />
Fixes should be done without forcing anyone to grind for them.  We are broken, we should be fixed.<br />
<br />
Were warriors (when they were broken) forced to do AA's to fix themselves?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Um, yes they were, to a degree. Grinding is a part of EQ. Wake up. Its gonna be a part of WoW. Its a part of CoH. Its a part of EVERY progressive game there is and ever will be. Accept that.<br />
 <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Spiritblood</b><br /><i>If you are ever hired as a dev for a game please let me know in advance so I dont waste any time thinking about whether I should buy it or not :-)</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Lets hear your solutions Spiritblood? Heres a question for you. Are all shaman equal? Is the shaman who plays 40 hours a week not ENTITLED to be farther along and more powerful than the shaman who plays 10 hours a week? How do you achieve this? Listening to any options at this point. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>AA are not the answer and are in fact just another way to separate the player base, this time based on ability to grind. One of the themes I feel I have seen regardless of the uber vs casual person arguing has been that artificial separation of the playerbase is bad. </i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Look, there is NO POSSIBLE WAY to avoid a seperation of the player base at this point. I am offering an alternative that actually makes it POSSIBLE for less-active shaman to choose a path of progression for their character that equally available to EVERY SINGLE PERSON. Once again, are you trying to tell me that the 10 hour a week Shaman and the 40 hour a week one should be completely equal in all regards and aspects? Give me a break man.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>You also make it for the attention of the SoE folks, why? Before an idea is presented to them shouldn't it be agreed on?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>This is my personal idea, an idea for them to CONSIDER. I never claimed this idea to be the consensus of all shamans here. I made it to their attention because SO MANY good ideas are probably not even seen by them because they are completly smothered in the middle of threads that are 90% worthless posts no one wanted to read. These people don't have time to sift through these threads, nor should they.  Wanna rename it "My Personal Idea on a Solution, Not meant to represent the views of any other shaman who ever played EQ" I will. I could care less. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>This undermines the big argument going on about Shaman being broken, because instead of pushing for fixes, you are pushing for fixes over time, at the discretion of the shaman. So, if I want to be fixed and useful I have to grind 200 aa.<br />
<br />
Thanks Blazz, I really appreciate that.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No, it offers a solution to the fact that pre-Gates, SHAMAN ARE NOT NEARLY AS BROKEN AS PEOPLE THINK. Gates and above is where the GLARING deficiencies of our class begin to emerge. Pre-EP Shaman are an EXTREMELY powerful class, even in just Bazaar gear. <br />
<br />
Advancement and reward based on time. That is EQ. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Gloriana</b><br /><i>Changed the title of the thread. Please don't address the developers as if you were speaking for the entire community <img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="smile" smilieid="1" /></i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Sorry, not my intention, was just offering them another idea. But I want them to see it. <br />
<br />
All in all, I think the people who disagree are missing the bigger picture. Rewards based on time spent are viable game concepts. Isnt this EXACTLY what the non-raiders are complaining about? That they cannot get to the same "level" of gear and zone access with a similar amount of time spent? I am proposing a DIRECTLY linear reward system acessible by EVERYONE based on time spent in the game.<br />
<br />
I seriously see you people that disagree with me as the BIGGEST part of the problem. You want more for less. You want rewards without dedication. You want Diablo 2, where anyone can log in for 5 minutes and be maxxed out. You want total equality with the guy who plays 5 times as much as you do. <br />
<br />
Speaking for myself, I would be LUCKY to be able to progress halfway along one of my proposed "trees". I just do not play that much anymore. I have neither the desire nor the patience to grind. But IF I WANTED TOO I COULD. What is the Number 1 "non-raider" complaint? Its that they do not get equal reward for time spent in the game because they choose not to raid. I am suggesting time based linear equality.</p>
	
	
	
