I am not saying all shaman should be equal. I am saying that you are trying to create a pathway that is open to people who have been online for a long time and ground their way to a high number of aa. Not all these people raid, and not all raiders have a high number of aa.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I am trying to create a pathway for people who have invested more time in their characters that doesnt involve raids, flags, uber gear, etc. The fact that not all "end game flagged " shamans do not have a high number of AA is exactly my point. They should be THAT much better than the guy who chooses not to raid but has the same AA based on zone access and flags? Give players the ability to upgrade themselves in ways other than gear and zones available. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>This is where your argument fails. Not all Gates and above Shaman have several hundred aa's. The way that Gates and above shaman have been able to get to that position is flags Blazz, not time spent in game. It's been about Advancement and reward based on flagging.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>No, this is exactly where my arguement is proven to be a potential solution. Let me give you some examples. Does the Bazaar shaman have access to any "advanced" focus effects like Marr's Gift, Druzzels Distance, Speed of Mithanial/Soulsec? Hell no, they get IH4, ER4, and SH4. All lower level than the focus's available on MANY advanced raid level items. People who choose not to raid are never going to see Marr's Gift. However, they could work the AA for "Extra Healing 1" and be as effecting as that uber shaman who has 1/4 of the days played and 1/3 of the AA. <br />
<br />
Reward based on flagging is pretty darn new. In addition to that, flaging itself is a function of time. Do you think its hard for Uqua and Qvic guilds to kill Fennin Ro or Xegony? Nope, its pretty trivial in fact, but it still takes ONE THING to get those flags for their members. TIME.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>No. It is not EQ.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>You tell me what EQ is then. Skill based? "Who you know" based? Its a game. MOST games of this kind reward for time spent. I am not talking about time standing in the Bazaar selling your good, I am talking about time spent improving your character and progressing forward in a semi-linear manner. Flagging allows people to skip that time investment and linear progression in SUCH a massive way its kinda hard to believe. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>Its an alarming way to head through life thinking that anyone who disagrees with you is the problem.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Not everyone, just the ones who seem to want the game handed to them on a platter. I know you are not like this. <br />
<br />
You have read my posts. I am arguing with people constantly. I never claimed guys like Murtak are the "problem" because he wants to be a better healer and I could care less. But I am sorry, anyone who cannot see that rewards should be available based on a linear progression of TIME is not seeing the issues properly. LDoN is a reward system based on time. The whole AA system is currently a linear reward system based on Time. Leveling, lots of quests (especially those that involve rare drops), tradeskills, etc etc, so many aspects of EQ are reward systems based on TIME. Why not expand this to help adjust balance more?It does now to a certain extent. Which is better, a 300 aa warrior or a 10 aa warrior. Which is more effective, a Shaman with Cannibilization or a Shaman who hasnt "grinded" that AA yet?</p>
	
	
	
