<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Karshak_rn</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Jun 2003<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
I am trying to create a pathway for people who have invested more time in their characters that doesnt involve raids, flags, uber gear, etc. The fact that not all "end game flagged " shamans do not have a high number of AA is exactly my point. They should be THAT much better than the guy who chooses not to raid but has the same AA based on zone access and flags? Give players the ability to upgrade themselves in ways other than gear and zones available. <br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I agree with this as long as it is not detrimental to those who are flagged. We know the game is split, and I am all for individuals to be able to progress their characters (big of me I know) but not at the expense of others. From my experience, and this is purely my perception, people who spend the majority of their time raiding make very little experience. People who spend their time grinding (or not raiding) make a bunch more. I am in the first bucket tthere and about 90 percent of my online time is raiding. The raiding guild I am a member of raids predominantly during the hours I am online. Sadly, I ding most of my aa during raids! I do have some very nice drops from raiding but I lack aa (160ish). I have some friends who were about the same in terms of character progression before I went over to the dark side. We still play around the same times but they have many many more aa than me, and I have much better stats. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
No, this is exactly where my arguement is proven to be a potential solution. Let me give you some examples. Does the Bazaar shaman have access to any "advanced" focus effects like Marr's Gift, Druzzels Distance, Speed of Mithanial/Soulsec? Hell no, they get IH4, ER4, and SH4. All lower level than the focus's available on MANY advanced raid level items. People who choose not to raid are never going to see Marr's Gift. However, they could work the AA for "Extra Healing 1" and be as effecting as that uber shaman who has 1/4 of the days played and 1/3 of the AA. <br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I see the problem, I just don't agree with the proposed solution. There should be less of a disparity in the focus effects available, but I would prefer to have those kinds of things be aa driven. Then, you could have a shaman with a bunch of aa's getting great focus effects, and as they are aa driven it wouldn't matter what gear they had. A raiding shaman could have the choice of grinding the extra aa or waiting for a drop with the effect. This kind of idea for aa progression might work, although I think it will make the non-raider feel that they are having to spend aa on things just to keep up.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
Reward based on flagging is pretty darn new. In addition to that, flaging itself is a function of time. Do you think its hard for Uqua and Qvic guilds to kill Fennin Ro or Xegony? Nope, its pretty trivial in fact, but it still takes ONE THING to get those flags for their members. TIME.<br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Yep, but its the evolution of the game. I am still a noob compared to some of you old timers, but even I have to crack a wry smile when I see someone go from the hedge maze to raiding potimeb in about 8 days. Granted their gear will suck for a while, but that kind of piggy backing and racing through content on the back of others efforts is laughable.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
You tell me what EQ is then. Skill based? "Who you know" based? Its a game. MOST games of this kind reward for time spent. I am not talking about time standing in the Bazaar selling your good, I am talking about time spent improving your character and progressing forward in a semi-linear manner. Flagging allows people to skip that time investment and linear progression in SUCH a massive way its kinda hard to believe. <br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I know everyone wants to think that you don't need much more than a pulse to be outstanding at EQ but there is an element of skill involved. Not skill as in clay pigeon shooting, or golf, but in anticipation, reaction, reacting the best way, executing your plan correctly. Shoot me for this but if there was no element of skill at all why are some players avoided and others sought after. There are times in the game when things occur and I look at the group and realize that they are very skillful players, and that my own in game experience was just heightened by being around them.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
Not everyone, just the ones who seem to want the game handed to them on a platter. I know you are not like this. <br />
</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I am glad you realize this. I might disagree with you, but I certainly don't want the game handed to anyone. I like EQ because it is hard. It's annoying as hell sometimes, but there are those little moments that just make you realize why you play. If you don't have those then it's time to quit. While I am having less of them now, I still get them occasionally.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Blazz</b><br /><i><br />
You have read my posts. I am arguing with people constantly. I never claimed guys like Murtak are the "problem" because he wants to be a better healer and I could care less. But I am sorry, anyone who cannot see that rewards should be available based on a linear progression of TIME is not seeing the issues properly. LDoN is a reward system based on time. The whole AA system is currently a linear reward system based on Time. Leveling, lots of quests (especially those that involve rare drops), tradeskills, etc etc, so many aspects of EQ are reward systems based on TIME. Why not expand this to help adjust balance more?It does now to a certain extent. Which is better, a 300 aa warrior or a 10 aa warrior. Which is more effective, a Shaman with Cannibilization or a Shaman who hasnt "grinded" that AA yet?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>I think that there can be multiple paths to progress by, and choosing one should not close another. Have effects attainable by aa for the grinder, and have effects on gear for the raider. BUT, don't tie base functionality to aa. No shaman, from BoT to Kod'Taz should have to suffer from a different base heal, or resists on a slow. <br />
For what its worth I absolutely agree with you on the amount of aa making a player better. I guess my point is that a non raiding shaman will probably have a much higher probability of being close to maxed out healing aa than a raiding shaman (moi). I would be irritated if a new tree came out and I was suddenly 25aa from starting to improve my base heals for example.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
