	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>I agree with this as long as it is not detrimental to those who are flagged. </i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Honestly, IMHO, I think it gives folks who choose not to raid a chance to be ALMOST as good as Raid equiped players through AA. But also remember, while people who raid a ton may not make as MUCH XP, they still make XP. I have 200, and I rarely push-grind. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>I see the problem, I just don't agree with the proposed solution. There should be less of a disparity in the focus effects available, but I would prefer to have those kinds of things be aa driven. Then, you could have a shaman with a bunch of aa's getting great focus effects, and as they are aa driven it wouldn't matter what gear they had. A raiding shaman could have the choice of grinding the extra aa or waiting for a drop with the effect. This kind of idea for aa progression might work, although I think it will make the non-raider feel that they are having to spend aa on things just to keep up.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>This is almsot exactly what I am talking about though. Also, when you start factoring in Tribute, which is REALLY quite economical and simple to use (heck, go clean out Sol A, farm the FS, trib the drops, shrug, easy as pie) then everyone really has a path to a DARN solid character without the current "walls" we have now. The Raid shaman can get that much more efficient for his enviroment, and the non-raid shaman has a chance to get some nice abilities with his "extra" aaxp. It seems win-win to me. I think if you ask most non-raiding players, they dont MIND spending time to keep up, but they cant keep up now. Ask most Raiders what the problem are, and they will tell you they are JUST a teensy bit ineffective enough to contribute effectively. Adding the ability to grow to both class of player sounds fair. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>I am still a noob compared to some of you old timers, but even I have to crack a wry smile when I see someone go from the hedge maze to raiding potimeb in about 8 days. Granted their gear will suck for a while, but that kind of piggy backing and racing through content on the back of others efforts is laughable.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>Thats just it, and honestly it applies at all levels. I raid, but I am in a slower paced, more family style guild. We arent the speediest through content, but we have a solid membership. We play a lot. We raid a lot. We hang together in groups a lot. There is nothing wrong with content skippers. Personally, I could care less what ANYONE else has. But I want to be able to maintain MY effectiveness in MY enviroment, and I am starting to have difficulty doing that. Xegoney raid the other night was great. 3 shaman, 1 to RGC the MA, 2 others to slow and malos the adds as the waves come in, and guard the chanters when the inattentive break mez. I felt EXTREMELY useful. Then, Fennin Ro, I feel like a baby brother at the Drive IN with my older brother and his date. Yeah, I Bane Fennin, wee. Bane, heal heal heal, so what. NOt like the MA ever got under 80 anywy, guy has 12K hps and 3K ac or something. I dunno. Little extra damage, or healing, and I would be doing SOMETHING. But my mesly 80 dps and 1400-1700 heals didnt even seem to help. <blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>I know everyone wants to think that you don't need much more than a pulse to be outstanding at EQ but there is an element of skill involved. Not skill as in clay pigeon shooting, or golf, but in anticipation, reaction, reacting the best way, executing your plan correctly. Shoot me for this but if there was no element of skill at all why are some players avoided and others sought after. There are times in the game when things occur and I look at the group and realize that they are very skillful players, and that my own in game experience was just heightened by being around them.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>EQ definitely has a fairly decent skill factor. I am not saying its TOTALLY simple. But, the less skilled players can easily hide in guilds. LDoN certainly showed people for what kind of skill player they were, especially those first few weeks of it. I had people in my own guild I groaned when I saw in the group, heh. But honestly, if you are half competent and have time, you can advance, easily. You can go from 1-65 and 500 aa and never enter a dungeon. Just the nature of the game.<blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Karshak_rn</b><br /><i>I think that there can be multiple paths to progress by, and choosing one should not close another. Have effects attainable by aa for the grinder, and have effects on gear for the raider. BUT, don't tie base functionality to aa. No shaman, from BoT to Kod'Taz should have to suffer from a different base heal, or resists on a slow. <br />
For what its worth I absolutely agree with you on the amount of aa making a player better. I guess my point is that a non raiding shaman will probably have a much higher probability of being close to maxed out healing aa than a raiding shaman (moi). I would be irritated if a new tree came out and I was suddenly 25aa from starting to improve my base heals for example.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>This is a legitimate point, but on the other side of the equation is that the "functionality" is attainable by everyone. Its not something that is divided like spells dropping in high-end zones, or the best of the best focus only on raid gear. You would be 25 aa from a better base heal, but honestly, dont YOU, and probably 90% of the rest of the raid shamans in the game, already have a bunch of healing AAs? I sure do. EP mobs hit hard and I like to keep my chantys alive (I let the wizards die though, if they get hit, they deserve it heh)<br />
<br />
I think the idea has merit, and should be considered. I dislike the artificial seperration we have now. I have no Gates spells, I have no time to get flagged for KT, I am struggling to raid enough nights to get a new item a month. But if I had a chance to better myself in a significant way with XP, it would make anyting seem more worthwhile, it would establish goals that are real, and achievable, no matter WHAT level I am playing at. And, best of all, anyone can do it. So my friend who hates to raid can become a 2K healer, without Marrs Gift. And my other friend can actually be a SOLID healer in his raids with Marrs. Everyone seems to win.</p>
	
	
	
