	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Ghost of Rommel</b><br /><i>Also weather or not your playing fourty hours our ten your paying the same about and should be offered the same opportunities..</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote>How is having upgrades to spells tied to AA not offering EVERYONE the same opportunities? <br />
<br />
Currently, the game is VERY VERY divided, those who raid, and those who do not raid. The people who do not raid do not have the same opportunities as those who raid (not opening the "why dont they just raid" debate here).<br />
<br />
Also if you read my initial post, the method of balancing I am suggesting works fairly well on all levels of play. Higher end raid end-game characters can pursue AA that will balance them better for the content they are playing, while lower end non-raiding shaman can pursue AA that will give them increased abilities that they really do not have available through Focus, like Marrs Gift (compared to IH4) or Speed of Soulsec and Mith (compared to Spell Haste 4) or Preservation of Xegoney (compared to MP4) etc etc. <br />
<br />
Please do not sit there and tell me there is HUGE problems with the shaman class "across the board" either. While mid-range shamans indeed have SOME balance issues, the same can be said for almost every class. Shaman are EXTREMELY powerful in mid-raing content (low-mid PoP, High Luclin, mid-Gates) but their effectivness drops off exponentially the closer to the "high end" you get. This system, or one like it, would make EVERYONE able to pursue the path to the type of Shaman they wanted to make.</p>
	
	
	
