<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>BlargX</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2001<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>The idea of advancement being tied to time is a terrible one.  <br />
<br />
The chance that anyone would buy any game if they knew that was its premise up front is next to nil.  Just try to imagine anyone picking up a box saying that the main way to advance in a game is to spend more time in it.<br />
<br />
Advancement should come through the application of intelligence and perhaps intelligence unorthodoxly applied.  Being smart enough to do things well and also finding out the shortcuts, the way to do things the best way possible in the shortest length of time, is the challenge for me.  Speed is an essential ingredient, and directly ties to the intelligence of the player as an objective measure of his ability to accomplish.  Merely spending time is no accomplishment at all; it's how you spend it and how little of it you need to spend to achieve your goals.  A game is not a longevity contest.  We're all going to die anyway, and I don't have to come to a game to do it in real time.  <br />
<br />
A further challenge comes in some games from putting my knowledge and insight and attempts to be clever and deceptive to work against others in some games, like say poker or chess.<br />
<br />
Merely plodding along using up time doesn't figure into my picture of mastery at all, and shouldn't be particularly rewarded.  Any fool can just use up all his time.  <br />
<br />
Indeed, in both games and sports, it isn't merely practicing that makes you accomplished; it's practicing the RIGHT way.  Using the right training and drills is not only better than using the wrong ones; using the wrong drills can keep you at the same level forever, or even make you worse the longer you do them.<br />
<br />
Yet though merely using up time is neither fun in itself nor challenging in the least, it should be made the major focal point of a game?<br />
<br />
What kind of accomplishment is that to celebrate -- that one merely spent more time than the other guy?  In every other situation I can think of, the more time you spend getting somewhere, the greater your failure.<br />
<br />
In games, I like that you start from an even playing field, where everyone can excel.  The rules are the same whether you're young or old, rich or poor.  The fun and accomplishment is available to everyone depending on their skill and application.<br />
<br />
Starting from that even playing field, I like to work at outsmarting other people and surpassing my own limitations, gaining knowledge and skill as fast as I can.  If I'm great at a game, it will go faster.  If I'm not, it will go slower.  But in no case will it be about time directly; it will be about my abillity to apply myself and achieve over time.<br />
<br />
Tying time closely to achievement is a recipe for boredom.  I doubt anyone will ever move a single game box off a shelf by telling them that their cleverness and intelligence will rank distantly behind their ability to just put in hours.<br />
<br />
That's the opposite of a game, or fun.  That's more like a dead-end job.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
