<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Blazz</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Mystic<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Sep 2003<br />
	Location: Upstate, NY
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>Blarg, this kind of game atmosphere would be fantastic if there was a new, free expansion coming out every 2 months, but lets look at the realities of the situation in ANY online game, but especially EQ.<br />
<br />
The game is solved. They all are. Period. You cannot pump out enough content to keep "skill" as a highly influentual factor in advancement. After a while EVERYTHING becomes a grind, be it LDoN, XPing, farming pp for buying upgrades, raid-farming, etc etc. The newness of any event, zone, quest or camp becomes old in a rather short period of time, no matter what or where. <br />
<br />
What has EQ always been about? Reward for time spent, basically, up to a point. XPing isnt rocket science. Going after loot doesnt take a genius. <br />
<br />
This whole "marketing" arguement I see is completely ridiculous as well. EQ is ALREADY about massinve time-sinks. Do you see it written on the box? Get real,  no company is going to put the inattractive features of their game on the box. Here is something though, that MIGHT get put on the OoW box if this system was implemented:<br />
<br />
Advance along the path YOU choose! Shamans want to be better Healers? YOU can choose! Wizards want to have better Cold Damage? YOU follow that path! Clerics want more offensive power? YOU make that choice on YOUR character!<br />
<br />
I honestly though people like you, Blarg, and Snow and Iz and the other advocates for more equality between the raider and the non-raider would be somewhat open to this kind of idea. After all, isnt a "linear path to progression regardless of playstyle" what you are all asking for?<br />
<br />
See what I mean? Any good marketing company can take something that is relatively negative and spin it back.</p>
	
	
	
